%N A391777 Total number of 231 patterns in all heapable permutations of length n.
%C A391777 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A391777 A 231-pattern in a heapable permutation p=(p1,p2..pn) is a triad of indices i<j<k where pk<pi<pj.
%H A391777 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%H A391777 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A391777/a391777.py.txt">Python Program</a>
%e A391777 For n=4 the heapable permutations are:
%e A391777   (1,2,3,4): no 231 patterns.
%e A391777   (1,3,2,4): no 231 patterns.
%e A391777   (1,2,4,3): no 231 patterns.
%e A391777   (1,3,4,2): (3,4,2) => 1 231 pattern.
%e A391777   (1,4,2,3): no 231 patterns.
%e A391777 So among the 5 heapable permutations of length 4:
%e A391777   4 permutation have 0 231 patterns,
%e A391777   1 permutation has 1 231 pattern,
%e A391777   for a total of 1 132 patterns.
